Total monthly takings are in thousands of Australian dollars.

  1. Load the data and calculate the average cost of a nights accommodation in Victoria each month (i.e.,Cost variable).
# Load the data
load(file = "motel.rda")
roomnights <- ts(motel[,1], start = 1980, frequency = 12)
takings <- ts(motel[,2]*1000, start = 1980, frequency = 12)
cpi <- ts(motel[,3], start = 1980, frequency = 12)
cost <- takings / roomnights
autoplot(cost)

  1. Plot the CPI and Cost time series.
tsdisplay(cpi)

tsdisplay(cost)

autoplot(cpi)+autolayer(cost)

  1. Plot the Cost time series against the CPI time series and calculate the correlation between CPI and Cost.
plot(cpi, cost, xlab="CPI", ylab="Cost")

cor(cpi,cost)
## [1] 0.9907186

Discuss your results and explain why the logarithms of both variables need to be taken before fitting any models.

Reason: From the time series plots, we know that the variance for both of them are changing as their means changing. In other words, the variance of both variables are not constant. Thus, we need the logarithms transformation for CPI and Cost to stabilize their variance.

Result: From the plot of cost against cpi, we can see that those two variables are strongly correlated with each other : as one increases, the other one also increases. They also have large value of correlation (0.9907186).

  1. Use the linear model with time series components function tslm() to fit a linear model to the () time series as a function of the () time series (i.e., CPI Independent variable, Cost Dependent variable).
lm.cost_cpi <- tslm(log(cost) ~ log(cpi))
lm.cpi_cost <- tslm(log(cpi) ~ log(cost))
  1. Plot () against () and the fitted trend.
plot(log(cost), log(cpi))
lines(as.numeric(log(cost)), lm.cpi_cost$fitted.values, type="l",col=2)

plot(log(cpi), log(cost))
lines(as.numeric(log(cpi)), lm.cost_cpi$fitted.values, type="l",col=2)

From the plot, we can see that those two variables are strongly correlated with each other and there is a clear positive trend.

The tslm() method fits a linear model to the log(cost) time series as a function of the log(cpi) time series, with a intercept of -1.682 and a slope of 1.303, meaning that for every 1 unit increase of log(cpi), there is 1.303 unit increase of log(cost). Same idea for the tslm() fitting to log(cpi) to log(cost), with 1.334 as the intercept and 0.757 as the slope.

In terms of the residuals of the tslm models, there are clearly some patterns remaining in the residuals and the plot of residuals is not white noise since the acf graph shows significant difference and the distribution is not normal enough.

  1. Use the auto.arima() function to fit an appropriate regression model with ARIMA errors to the Cost and CPI time series(i.e., CPI Independent variable, Cost Dependent variable). Set the Order of seasonaldifferencing argument, D, to 1 and the lambda argument to 0 to reflect a logarithmic transformation.
model.arima <- auto.arima(y=cost,xreg=cpi,D=1,lambda = 0)
  1. Use the summary() function to summarize the generated model.

Discuss your results.

The auto.arima() function generates a model of Regression with ARIMA(0,1,1)(0,1,2)[12] errors, with an AICc of -863.79 and BIC of -848.38. The acf of this models residuals doesnt show a sign of significant difference and its distribution is normal, which means that it is now close to a white noise. The ljung-box test also prove this point with a large p value of 0.3223 (>0.05). Thus this model of regression with arima better captures the information in the data.
